                                            <div type="typology">
                                                <p>Eastern › Syro-Palestinian › Central Syrian</p>
                                                <p>Urban, sedentary dialect, high-prestige variety</p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div>
                                                <head>General</head>
                                                <p>The dialect of the capital of Syria is regarded as a very “elegant”
            variety of Arabic and has a very high prestige. It is
            frequently used in the media and increasingly also in films. Hence, 
            Damascus Arabic is widely understood in whole Syria, in Lebanon,
            and even in Jordan and Palestine.</p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="researchHistory">
                                                <p>
                                                    Descriptions of the Arabic dialect of Damascus go back as far as
            the 18th century when the German orientalist and theologian
            Johann Heinrich Callenberg published his description of Damascus Arabic in Latin (
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==callenberg_johann_heinrich_001">Callenberg 1720-1740</ref>
                                                    ). 
Collections of texts and short grammatical
            notes were published at the end of the 19th and the first half
            of the 20th centuries (Huart 1883, Oestrup 1897 [although mostly
            not real Damascene dialect], Malinjoud 1924, Bergsträßer 1924,
            Saussey 1937-38), Cantineau 1956, Dietrich 1956) but the first
            comprehensive description of the dialect appeared only in the 1960s:
            Cowell 1964, Grotzfeld 1964, Grotzfeld 1965, Ambros 1977.
            Today Damascus Arabic is certainly among the Arabic dialects
            which are best described.
                                                </p>
                                                <p>A concise grammatical sketch of the dialect is Jérôme Lentin’s “Damascus Arabic”, in EALL I, 546-555.</p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="dictionaries">
                                                <p>Stowasser, Karl; Ani, Moukhtar: English-Damascus Arabic. Georgetown 1964.</p>
                                                <p>Barthélemy 1935-54 is still unmatched as the dictionary for Syrian Arabic, but it
            is mainly based on the dialect of Aleppo. Nevertheless it is extremely useful for
            Damascus Arabic too, as is Denizeau 1960.</p>
                                                <p>Very promising is the online-dictionary titled Dictionnaire d’arabe dialectal syrien
            (parler de Damas) by Claude Salamé &amp;amp;amp; Jérôme Lentin, although until now only the letter
            B has been published.</p>
                                                <p>
                                                    Our site provides a digital dictionary of Damascus Arabic.
                                                    <ptr target="apc_eng_002"/>
                                                </p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="textBooks">
                                                <p>Aldoukhi, Rima; Procházka, Stephan; Telič, Anna. Lehrbuch des Syrisch-Arabischen 1: Praxisnaher Einstieg in den Dialekt von Damaskus. Unter Mitarbeit von Narine Grigoryan. Wiesbaden: Harrassowitz, 2014.</p>
                                                <p>Aldoukhi, Rima; Procházka, Stephan; Telič, Anna. Lehrbuch des Syrisch-Arabischen 2: Damaszenisch für Fortgeschrittene. Unter Mitarbeit von Narine Grigoryan. Wiesbaden: Harrassowitz, 2014.</p>
                                                <p>Cantineau &amp;amp;amp; Helbaoui: Manuel élémentaire d’arabe oriental (parler de Damas). 1953.</p>
                                                <p>Ferguson &amp;amp;amp; Ani: Damascus Arabic. 1965.</p>
                                                <p>Rice &amp;amp;amp; Sa’id: Eastern Arabic. 1979</p>
                                                <p>Liddicoat, Lennane, Abdul Rahim: Syrian colloquial Arabic: a functional course. 1999.</p>
                                            </div>
